# Drizzle Zod Schema Generation

When a feature interacts with a database table, its `.types.ts` must derive Zod schemas from the Drizzle schema using `drizzle-zod` — never hand-write Zod schemas for DB columns.

## Required imports

```typescript
import { createSelectSchema, createInsertSchema, createUpdateSchema } from "drizzle-zod";
import { searches } from "@/infra/db/schema.ts";
```

## Usage

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — hand-written Zod schema duplicating DB columns
export const storedSearchSchema = z.object({
  id: z.uuid(),
  query: z.string(),
  status: z.enum(["running", "paused"]),
  createdAt: z.date(),
});

// ✅ GOOD — derived from Drizzle schema
export const storedSearchSchema = createSelectSchema(searches);
export const createSearchSchema = createInsertSchema(searches);
export const updateSearchSchema = createUpdateSchema(searches);
export type StoredSearch = z.infer<typeof storedSearchSchema>;
```

## Refinements

Use the second argument to extend or narrow fields without redefining the full schema:

```typescript
export const createSearchSchema = createInsertSchema(searches, {
  query: (schema) => schema.min(1),
  status: z.literal("running"),
});
```

## Rules

- One `createSelectSchema` / `createInsertSchema` / `createUpdateSchema` per table the feature uses
- Use `.pick()` / `.omit()` to scope request schemas (e.g. omit `id` and `createdAt` from insert)
- Non-DB types (request params, API-only shapes) can still be plain Zod or interfaces
- All Drizzle table definitions live in `src/infra/db/schema.ts` — never define tables in feature files
